            "answer_text": "Well\u2026 they \u201cappear\u201d bad, because there are so many of them out there in the hands of consumers. Chances are, you know many people in your life with HP products, if not HP computers. Out of all of them, I bet at least one is having problems. Is that because HP sucks? Well\u2026 it has more to do with the numbers. Squaretrade did a study of laptops that customers had signed up for their aftermarket insurance for\u2026 the extended plans. They found that over three years, 16% of the best laptops failed\u2026 and 27% of the worst laptops failed. Yes, HP was at the bottom. Toshiba was at the top\u2026 but the sample of Toshiba laptops in the \u201cstudy\u201d was close to one tenth that of the HP owners. They released the study in 2009. That\u2019s the graphic you usually see with Asus at the top, Toshiba next to it, Apple in the middle, and HP at the bottom\u2026. or Asus to the left and HP to the right.  Anyway. With the smaller pool of failures, the rate wasn\u2019t as accurate as the larger pool of HP. This doesn\u2019t mean that more cheapskates didn\u2019t buy the low end HP stuff that the make to really not last longer than three years\u2026 \u2026 because HP is in the business to make money. They make money by selling laptop frequently, not selling laptops that last forever no matter what price point you purchase in at. I\u2019ve seen what happens time and time again with DV7 laptops and the brass screw anchors that are set into the plastic casing to hold the hinge screws in place\u2026 you know\u2026 IMPORTANT screws? The kind of screws that when the come out, the hinge no longer opens, and instead the entire assembly turns and grinds away at everything in its path like a T-Rex jaw (Ok, Velociraptor for size I guess)\u2026 with those now broken free brass ridged stubbs adding to the fray. It is not pretty. Typically catastrophic to the bottom casing, sometimes catastrophic to the motherboard. Designed to fail in choice of materials under normal expected strain. It happened to dozens of DV7\u2019s that I\u2019ve seen over the past three years. I\u2019m not pointing the finger and saying \u201cEvil HP\u201d. They are being as smart as they can. I\u2019ve talked about how currently they sell desktop computers that are no more than laptop motherboards in boxes. No expansion slots. They use laptop power supply bricks. But\u2026 they are the size of a slimline computer\u2026 and they sell slimline computers with expansions slots that will take standard low profile cards sold in the SAME CASES\u2026 just different models. No, the budget models that you see for $249 on sale at the big stores? Check the back. If it has that small, round hole for a laptop power connection instead of the big one you\u2019d normally see in a desktop\u2026 there\u2019s a laptop board in there. Why? They realized that there\u2019s a market of people out there who buy desktops because they\u2019ve always bought desktops. They never add to the computer, and they use it for light tasks. So. They built that machine. That, exact machine. And.. made it look like all the other machines. They tried the cute little blue cube\u2026 that didn\u2019t sell. Same concept, but looked too different. So\u2026 they relegated that smaller form factor to the professional community who can appreciate paying $900 for a Core i7 computer the size of a USB hub. When you look at their professional grade stuff, the failure rate drops. If you got a bad HP, I\u2019m sorry. There do seem to be a lot of them\u2026 but that is also because there are a TON of them out there. If your HP isn\u2019t holding up as well as you\u2019d like\u2026 it\u2019s probably because they want you to get a new one. Even if you aren\u2019t ready. ",
